steps.description:
Turn the chips after they’ve been in the oil for over 30 seconds, to brown each side. Only drop two or three chips into the pot of oil at a time (depending on the size pot you are using). You want each chip to have room to fry and not stick to each other. The amount you can add may vary depending on the size of the pot you're using; just be sure to keep the frying chips separated. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/df/Make-Homemade-Potato-Chips-Using-Safflower-Oil-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Homemade-Potato-Chips-Using-Safflower-Oil-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/d/df/Make-Homemade-Potato-Chips-Using-Safflower-Oil-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/aid2351162-v4-728px-Make-Homemade-Potato-Chips-Using-Safflower-Oil-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"486","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Cook the chips until they're golden brown and the bubbling oil calms. Use chopsticks or tongs to handle frying chips. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/84/Make-Homemade-Potato-Chips-Using-Safflower-Oil-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Homemade-Potato-Chips-Using-Safflower-Oil-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/8/84/Make-Homemade-Potato-Chips-Using-Safflower-Oil-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/aid2351162-v4-728px-Make-Homemade-Potato-Chips-Using-Safflower-Oil-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"486","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/">Creative Commons</a><br>
